In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims September 15 through October 15 as National Hispanic Heritage Month. He highlights the contributions of Hispanic Americans to the country, including their involvement in the military, economic prosperity, education, and scientific advancements. The President emphasizes the importance of embracing diversity and the dreams of equality and boundless opportunity. He mentions the establishment of the César E. Chávez National Monument and the need to continue working towards social justice. President Obama also discusses the Affordable Care Act and the efforts to provide healthcare coverage to uninsured Latinos. He expresses his commitment to passing comprehensive immigration reform and creating a thriving middle class accessible to all Americans, including the Hispanic community. The President concludes by calling upon public officials, educators, librarians, and all Americans to observe National Hispanic Heritage Month with appropriate ceremonies and activities.